'''Henchir-Belli''' also known as '''Beled Belli''' is a location and archaeological site in [[Tunisia]].

==History ==
[[File:Roman Empire - Africa Proconsularis (125 AD).svg|thumb|right| Africa Proconsularis (125 AD)]]Known as Belali  it was a [[Roman Empire|Roman-era]] [[civitas]] in the [[Roman province]] of  [[Africa Proconsularis]].<ref>Barrington Atlas, 2000, pl. 32 E4.</ref> Column ruins of an ancient [[Roman temple|temple]]/[[church building|church]] are still found in situ.<ref>Michael Greenhalgh, ''The Military and Colonial Destruction of the Roman Landscape of North Africa''. (BRILL, 8 May 2014 ) p90.</ref>

The ancient city was also the seat of an ancient [[bishopric]],<ref>[https://translate.google.com.au/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t0290.htm&prev=search  Titular Episcopal See of  Belali].</ref><ref>Pius Bonifacius Gams, ''Series Episcoporum Ecclesiae Catholicae'', (Leipzig, 1931), p. 464.</ref> in the [[ecclesiastical province]] of [[Carthage]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/d2b39.html  Belali] at catholic-hierarchy.org.</ref> The only known [[bishop]] from antiquity is Adeodato ([[floruit|fl.]]411).  The [[bishopric]] survives today as a [[titular see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]],<ref>Stefano Antonio Morcelli, ''Africa Christiana'', Volume I, (Brescia, 1816), p98-99.</ref><ref>David M. Cheney [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/d2b39.html  Belali] at catholic-hierarchy.org.</ref> [[Carlos Alberto de Pinho Moreira Azevedo]] being [[bishop]] since 2004.<ref>''Le Petit Episcopologe'', Issue 179, Number 14,844.</ref>

